<subSubSection id="C30FB2903524FFE8FF47FA1DFBFFF98A" pageId="7" pageNumber="363" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3524FFE8FF47FA1DFBFFF98A" blockId="7.[151,1437,1447,2014]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B9613D093524FFE8FF47FA1DFEE1F9F5" bold="true" box="[199,334,1519,1545]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after the Wayuu mythical character “Wale’kerü”, a spider that teach the art of knitting to Wayuu womens. The Wayuu or Guajiro language, of the Arawakan family of languages, belongs to the Wayuu people, a native American ethnic group that inhabits the region of the 
<typeStatus id="54AE5FB93524FFE8FC3EF9CAFC41F9AE" box="[958,1006,1592,1618]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">type</typeStatus>
locality. To be treated as an arbitrary combination of letters, and hence without the need to agree in gender with the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30FB2903524FFE8FF47F98DFB99F91D" pageId="7" pageNumber="363" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3524FFE8FF47F98DFB99F91D" blockId="7.[151,1437,1447,2014]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B9613D093524FFE8FF47F98DFEEDF965" bold="true" box="[199,322,1663,1689]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C159A983524FFE8FE35F972FD95F965" authority="Muñoz-Charry &amp; Galvis &amp; Martínez, 2022" authorityName="Muñoz-Charry &amp; Galvis &amp; Martínez" authorityYear="2022" box="[437,570,1663,1689]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lapsias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="walekeru" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B9613D093524FFE8FE35F972FD95F965" box="[437,570,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">L. walekeru</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9613D093524FFE8FDC1F98DFD33F965" bold="true" box="[577,668,1663,1689]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A25280723524FFE8FDC1F98DFD33F965" box="[577,668,1663,1689]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be recognized from those of the remaining species in the genus by their longer and thick dorsal tibial apophysis (dTa) that overpass two thirds of the cymbium, hook–like median apophysis (ma) located posteriorly in the retrolateral side of the bulb (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3524FFE8FC26F935FB86F91D" box="[934,1065,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–31" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,349,1755]" captionTargetId="figure-85@8.[151,1436,345,1768]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 27–31. L. walekeru sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 10813), 27 habitus; 28, 31 left palp, ventral view; 29–30 same, retrolateral view.Abbreviations: dTa= dorsal tibial apophysis, e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 0.50 mm (27), 0.10 mm (28–31)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501140" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501140/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Figs 28–31</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30FB2903524FFE7FF47F919FE0DFF05" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="364" pageId="7" pageNumber="363" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3524FFE7FF47F919FB5BFF29" blockId="7.[151,1437,1447,2014]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,321]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="364" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B9613D093524FFE8FF47F919FD8EF8F9" bold="true" box="[199,545,1771,1797]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
Description. Male (
<typeStatus id="54AE5FB93524FFE8FE28F919FDBBF8F9" box="[424,532,1771,1797]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">holotype</typeStatus>
).
</emphasis>
Total length: 5.25. Carapace brown with a lateral stripe of white setae, 2.72 long, 1.93 wide, 1.90 high (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3524FFE8FE12F8FDFE47F8D5" box="[402,488,1807,1833]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–31" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,349,1755]" captionTargetId="figure-85@8.[151,1436,345,1768]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 27–31. L. walekeru sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 10813), 27 habitus; 28, 31 left palp, ventral view; 29–30 same, retrolateral view.Abbreviations: dTa= dorsal tibial apophysis, e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 0.50 mm (27), 0.10 mm (28–31)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501140" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501140/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
). OC light brown with eyes on dark marks and white setae, 1.32 long. Anterior eye row 1.74 wide and posterior 1.71 wide. Sternum yellow, 1.15 long, 0.93 wide. Labium yellow, 0.41 long, 0.57 wide. Chelicerae dark brown, with a beard of white setae, with one retromarginal and three promarginal teeth. Palp brown, with a strong embolus (e) arising prolaterally, median apophysis (ma) placed posteriorly, long and thick dorsal tibial apophysis (dTa) (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3524FFE8FED7F86DFE76F845" box="[343,473,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–31" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,349,1755]" captionTargetId="figure-85@8.[151,1436,345,1768]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 27–31. L. walekeru sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 10813), 27 habitus; 28, 31 left palp, ventral view; 29–30 same, retrolateral view.Abbreviations: dTa= dorsal tibial apophysis, e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 0.50 mm (27), 0.10 mm (28–31)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501140" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501140/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Figs 28–31</figureCitation>
). Leg formula: 4132, all brown with yellow marks. Leg macrosetae: femur, I–IV d 1 di, p 2 di; patella, I–II p 1 me; III–IV d 2 me; tibia, I v 2–2–2, p 0–0–1; II v 1–2–2; II p 1–0–1; III v 2–0–2, p 0–0–1, r 1–1–0; IV v 1–0–1, p 1–0–1, r 1–1–0; metatarsus, I–II v 2–0–2, p 0–1–1; II r 1–1–0; III v 2–0–2, p 1–1–2, r 1–1–2; IV v 1–0–2, p 1–2–2, r 1–1–2. Abdomen yellowish with a disperse pattern of brown spots (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E352BFFE7FB13FF49FB48FF29" box="[1171,1255,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–31" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,349,1755]" captionTargetId="figure-85@8.[151,1436,345,1768]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 27–31. L. walekeru sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 10813), 27 habitus; 28, 31 left palp, ventral view; 29–30 same, retrolateral view.Abbreviations: dTa= dorsal tibial apophysis, e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 0.50 mm (27), 0.10 mm (28–31)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501140" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501140/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="364">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B352BFFE7FF47FF2DFE0DFF05" blockId="8.[151,1436,151,321]" box="[199,418,223,249]" pageId="8" pageNumber="364">
<emphasis id="B9613D09352BFFE7FF47FF2DFE8AFF05" bold="true" box="[199,293,223,249]" pageId="8" pageNumber="364">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30FB290352BFFE7FF47FEF0FD55FEBD" pageId="8" pageNumber="364" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B352BFFE7FF47FEF0FD55FEBD" blockId="8.[151,1436,151,321]" pageId="8" pageNumber="364">
<emphasis id="B9613D09352BFFE7FF47FEF0FDB3FEE0" bold="true" box="[199,540,258,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="364">Distribution and Comments.</emphasis>
Known only from its 
<typeStatus id="54AE5FB9352BFFE7FC94FEF1FCEBFEE1" box="[788,836,259,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="364">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E352BFFE7FC2EFEF1FBADFEE1" box="[942,1026,258,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 57" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1890,1914]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,181,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-22@15.[164,1423,181,1866]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 57. Distribution of jumping spiders of the tribe Lapsiini Maddison (Salticidae: Spartaeinae) in South America. The figures with a dot inside represent the type species of each genus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501154/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="364">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus id="54AE5FB9352BFFE7FBC7FEF1FBD8FEE1" box="[1095,1143,259,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="364">type</typeStatus>
specimens were collected beating low vegetation, in a high-Andean moist forest.
</paragraph>
